    <note type="biography">
        <p>Geologist and army officer. Served in the British army, 1807–15. Noted for his work on the Silurian system. President of the Geological Society of London, 1831–3 and 1841–3; of the British Association for the Advancement of Science, 1846; of the Royal Geographical Society of London, 1843–4, 1851, 1857–8, 1862–70. Director-general of the Geological Survey of Great Britain, 1855. Knighted, 1863; created baronet, 1866. FRS 1826.</p></note>
